%N A395468 Decimal expansion of the area of the constructible squarable lune whose circular arcs have central angles in a 5:3 ratio and common chord of unit length.
%C A395468 One of the five constructible squarable lunes. It was discovered by the Finnish mathematician Martin Johan Wallenius (1731-1773) in 1766.
%C A395468 Called the "concave octagon lune" by Shelburne (2005).
%C A395468 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395468 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395468/a395468.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395468 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395468 Brian J. Shelburne, <a href="https://bshelburne.wittenberguniversity.org/TheFiveLunes120408.pdf">The Five Quadrable (Squarable) Lunes</a>, Wittenberg University Springfield, 2005.
%H A395468 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_08">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 8</a>.
%F A395468 Equals sqrt(375 + 70*sqrt(15) - 2*sqrt(15*(3265 + 794*sqrt(15))))/30.
%F A395468 Equals f(5*theta) - f(3*theta), where theta = A395472, and f(x) = x/sin(x)^2 - cot(x)/4.
%F A395468 Minimal polynomial: 21600000*x^8 - 36000000*x^6 + 8132000*x^4 - 205200*x^2 - 729.
%e A395468 0.180541899848636287062369461563015127202314789707864...
%t A395468 RealDigits[Sqrt[375 + 70*Sqrt[15] - 2*Sqrt[15*(3265 + 794*Sqrt[15])]]/30, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395468 (PARI) sqrt(375 + 70*sqrt(15) - 2*sqrt(15*(3265 + 794*sqrt(15))))/30
